featured_reviews.review_id: Jama Masjid Ludhiana is a historic mosque situated in the city of Ludhiana in the Indian state of Punjab. Here are some key points about the mosque:  - The mosque was built in the year 1913 by Sheikh Abdul Rahim, who was a wealthy businessman and a religious leader in the city. - Jama Masjid Ludhiana is located in the old city area of Ludhiana, near the Clock Tower and the Town Hall. - The mosque is one of the largest in the city and has a capacity to accommodate around 800 worshippers at a time. - The mosque's architecture is a blend of Mughal and Islamic styles and features ornate domes, minarets, and intricate carvings on the walls. - The main prayer hall of the mosque has a large carpet covering the entire space, and there are separate prayer areas for women. - The mosque is a popular destination for tourists, who come here to admire the beautiful architecture and experience the peaceful ambiance. - Every year, during the month of Ramadan, the mosque organizes special prayer sessions and distributes food to the needy, which attracts a large number of people from different parts of the city. - Although the mosque is primarily used for religious purposes, it also serves as an important cultural center in Ludhiana, and hosts a range of events and activities throughout the year.

The Jamia Masjid, Nathowal is situated in Nathowal of the Ludhiana district in the Indian State of Punjab.
In the 1947, Partition of India, 10 to 12 Muslim families of this village migrated to Pakistan but 50 families stayed back with the Sikh, who didn't allow them to leave. At that time they built a mosque for worship.[1] Now Nathowal has a population of around 7, 000 of which around 500 are Muslims.
Repair on the mosque contributed by Muslims,Hindus and Sikhs. Of the Rs2.5 million invested in the project, around Rs1.5 million have been contributed by Sikhs and Hindus.

featured_reviews.review_id: the biggest mosque in Ludhiana by area. It is just adjacent to PAU and thus also known by the name University Masjid or PAU Masjid. It is a very old Masjid and probably in existence since the time of Sanet Wali R.A who is also buried in the adjacent compound. After Partition, the Muslim population of the area migrated to Pakistan and this Masjid was abandoned. After the establishment of PAU, some Irani and Kashmiri students found the dilapidated mosque in a corner of the university and made efforts to revive it. It had been in a very bad condition and encroached upon. Muslim students worked hard to re-establish the Masjid again. Many people like Dr Zahir, Dr Sultan Dr Ishtiyaq etc who were the faculty and students at the time, contributed their time and energies to revive it. Now Masha Allah the mosque is in good condition and daily prayers are offered. It has a regular Imam and Muazzin. It is a property of Muslim waqf Board Punjab who manage it. But most of the affairs are taken care by an Intizamia committee comprising of respectable citizens of the city, university faculty and students. Some property of the mosque has been illegally occupied, like the residential quarter meant for Imam is still occupied by the family of previous Imam Sahab even after his passing away. The family also tried to erect a wall to separate the property from the Masjid. But Alhumdulilah that wall was broken twice in 2012 and in 2018 by the people. Efforts need to be made to evict the property of its illegal occupants. Similarly,  the Muslim graveyard near the Masjid has some rooms which also have been occupied. I hope and pray that this Masjid is restored to its glory and its property maintained.

featured_reviews.review_id:
Founding of Ahmadiyya Jama'at

On March 23rd, 1889 Hazrat Mirza Ghulam Ahmad (a) started taking oath of allegiance at the house of a spiritual preceptor Hazrat Sufi Ahmad Jan in the city of Ludhiana.
